Wheelchair tennis star Kgothatso Montjane, the first black South African woman to compete at Wimbledon, defeated Katharina Kruger of Germany 6-3 2-6 6-1 in Thursday's quarter-finals The 32-year-old Montjane, from Seshego in Limpopo, received a wildcard into the draw and is ranked no 8 in the world. She was up against her 28-year-old doubles partner, Kruger, the world no 6. She wrapped up the match in 80 minutes. “I am very happy that I won today’s match against Katharina Kruger, it was a nerve-racking match and got me very shaky when I lost the second set,” Montjane said afterwards. “After the second-set loss, I managed to get my momentum back and dominated the set to finally close it 6-1. I am extremely excited about the way I am playing at the moment and I am just letting this sink in then will focus on the next match.” READ MORE: Kgothatso Montjane: First black South African woman to play at Wimbledon Wimbledon debutante Montjane will now face world no 1 and reigning champion Diede de Groot of the Netherlands on Friday for a place in the final. On Thursday, De Groot edged Germany’s Sabine Ellerbrock in straight sets, 6-4 6-3. – African News Agency